{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01UW46aEHvuD1gc6qpVM5xwb","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Found the issue. In the StatefulSet command:\n\n```\nif [ \"$POD_NAME\" = \"crdb-cluster-1\" ]; then\n  HTTP_ADDR=\"127.0.0.1:8080\";\nelse\n  HTTP_ADDR=\"0.0.0.0:8080\";\nfi\n```\n\nWhen `POD_NAME` is `crdb-cluster-1`, it sets `HTTP_ADDR` to `127.0.0.1:8080` (localhost only). This means:\n1. crdb-cluster-1's HTTP server only listens on localhost\n2. The kubelet's readiness probe runs from the host network and can't reach the pod's localhost, so the probe to `http://<pod-ip>:8080/health?ready=1` fails\n3. This is a deliberately injected fault—the condition is backwards. All pods should bind to `0.0.0.0:8080`, or the condition should target a different pod for a specific reason. Looking at the replica status, I see 2 available and 2 ready, which suggests the third pod is stuck pending due to the failed readiness probe.\n\nActually, I'm noticing the StatefulSet is in the middle of a rolling update—`currentReplicas: 1` and `updatedReplicas: 2` with different revisions. The pod ages show crdb-cluster-0 is the original (111 seconds old) while crdb-cluster-1 and crdb-cluster-2 are newly updated (9 and 14 seconds old), which matches the revision split.\n\nThe problem is becoming clearer: the new revision has the bug with the hardcoded HTTP_ADDR values, so the updated pods can't become ready. The old revision presumably didn't have this issue, but now the StatefulSet spec itself contains the buggy command, meaning any further updates will propagate this problem. problem is the condition itself—it's binding pod 1 and 2 to localhost while pod 0 stays on all interfaces. The fix is straightforward: either remove the conditional entirely and use `0.0.0.0:8080` across the board, or change the localhost binding to match. I should patch the StatefulSet command to use the all-interfaces address consistently. Though I'm noticing the replica status seems inconsistent with what I'm seeing in the pod readiness—the counts don't quite add up, which might mean the status is lagging behind the actual state. The issue is that only `crdb-cluster-1` has the misconfigured HTTP address, while `crdb-cluster-2` should work normally. However, `crdb-cluster-2` might not be ready because the cluster needs a quorum of at least 2 nodes out of 3 to be healthy, and with only `crdb-cluster-0` functioning, the readiness check fails even though individual nodes might be up.\n\nThe solution is to patch the StatefulSet to remove the conditional logic that's setting the wrong HTTP address for `crdb-cluster-1`. Updating the command to remove the conditional logic and hardcode the HTTP address to listen on all interfaces.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4052,"cache_read_input_tokens":33155,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4052},"output_tokens":38,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f39a24d6-f279-4b08-a6aa-623bc4d0e523","uuid":"84e34005-09b0-4e2a-b0b8-f48af4ae14f5","request_id":"req_011CccCXHxg2fxy3jzxuCyUc"}
